The '''Buckley Baronetcy''', of [[Dinas Mawddwy|Mawddwy]] in the [[County of Merioneth]], was created in the Baronetage of the United Kingdom in 1868 for [[Sir Edmund Buckley, 1st Baronet|Edmund Buckley]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=23447 |date=4 December 1868 |page=6459}}</ref> a British landowner and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician. He owned the [[Hendre Ddu Slate and Slab Company]] and served from 1865 to 1878 as one of the two [[Member of Parliament|Members of Parliament]] (MPs) for the [[Newcastle-under-Lyme (UK Parliament constituency)|borough of Newcastle-under-Lyme]].

His son, also named Edmund Buckley, became the second Baronet on his father's death. The title became extinct in 1919 on the death of the second Baronet.

==Buckley baronets, of Mawddwy, Merioneth (1868)==
*[[Sir Edmund Buckley, 1st Baronet]] (1834–1910)
*[[Sir Edmund Buckley, 2nd Baronet]] (1861–1919)

