{{Expand Finnish|Kannabis#Suomi|date=December 2016}} 
'''Cannabis in Finland''' is illegal. The 50th chapter of the [[Criminal Code of Finland|Criminal Code]] criminalises all dealings with illegal narcotics, including the production, import, transport, sale, possession and use of cannabis.<ref name=RL>{{cite web|title=39/1889: The Criminal Code of Finland|url=http://www.finlex.fi/en/laki/kaannokset/1889/en18890039|website=Finlex|accessdate=6 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=kainulainen>{{cite web|last1=Kainulainen|first1=Heini|title=Huumeiden käyttäjien rikosoikeudellinen kontroll|url=http://www.haaste.om.fi/fi/index/lehtiarkisto/haaste32009/huumeidenkayttajienrikosoikeudellinenkontrolli.html|publisher=Haaste|accessdate=6 December 2016|language=Finnish}}</ref>

== History ==
The prohibition of cannabis in Finland dates back to 1966. The criminalisation of personal use has been controversial.<ref name=vks>{{cite web|title=VKS:2006:1 Seuraamuksen määrääminen huumausaineen käyttörikoksesta|url=http://www.vksv.fi/fi/index/julkaisutjaohjeet/valtakunnansyyttajanyleisetohjeet/syyteharkinta/vks20061seuraamuksenmaaraaminenhuumausaineenkayttorikoksesta.html|publisher=Finnish Office of the Prosecutor General|accessdate=6 December 2016|language=Finnish}}</ref> Personal use was made illegal in 1972. After a tie vote, the Grand Committee solved the issue by a [[random ballot]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Kriminologi: "Säännelty on parempi kuin laiton" - Kannabiksen kohtalosta päätettiin aikoinaan arvalla|url=http://www.ess.fi/uutiset/kotimaa/2014/09/13/kriminologi-saannelty-on-parempi-kuin-laiton---kannabiksen-kohtalosta-paatettiin-aikoinaan-arvalla|accessdate=21 January 2017|work=ESS.fi|date=13 September 2014|language=fi}}</ref>

== Personal use ==
The criminal procedure regarding personal use of illegal narcotics was reformed in 2001. The goal of the change was to relieve burden of personal use cases from the courts, expedite enforcement and standardise enforcement policies – specifically by stopping cases from not being prosecuted due to lack of resources. In the reformed procedure the police issue summary fines for most personal use offences, and cases are not brought to court unless the defendant so desires. Aggravated drug offences and possession with intent to redistribute (possession for sale) are always brought to court and penalties are harsher. In practice, possession of up to 10 grams of hashish or 15 grams of marijuana is deemed personal use and carries a penalty of 10–20 [[day-fine]]s.<ref name=vks />

== Medical cannabis ==
An extremely limited group of medicinal users (223 in 2014) are permitted to purchase [[Sativex]] mouth spray and/or Bedrocan, Bediol or Bedica brand herbal cannabis from one of 27 apothecaries that have the permit to sell [[medical cannabis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ita-savo.fi/uutiset/kotimaa/n%C3%A4m%C3%A4-27-apteekkia-ovat-myyneet-l%C3%A4%C3%A4kekannabista-180772|title=Nämä 27 apteekkia ovat myyneet lääkekannabista|work=Itä-Savo|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url = http://yle.fi/alueet/turku/2010/03/laakekannabiksen_kaytto_puhuttaa_1571689.html |title = Lääkekannabiksen käyttö puhuttaa &#124; Turku |publisher = yle.fi |date = 30 March 2010 |accessdate = 2011-02-17 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Silvàn|first1=Sini|title=Lääkekannabis edelleen marginaalinen lääke|url=http://yle.fi/aihe/artikkeli/2015/04/20/laakekannabis-edelleen-marginaalinen-laake|publisher=YLE|accessdate=6 December 2016|language=Finnish}}</ref>

