[[Image:Vilnius KGB Wiretap Room.jpg|thumb|250px|[[KGB]] telephone tapping room in [[Vilnius KGB Museum]], Lithuania]] '''[[Telephone tapping]] in the countries of the [[Eastern Bloc]]''' was a widespread method of the [[mass surveillance]] of the population by the [[secret police]].{{citation needed|date=June 2013}}
==History== In some countries, this was an open and legal practice. During [[martial law in Poland]], official censorship was introduced, including open phone tapping. In fact, the [[Służba Bezpieczeństwa|Polish secret police]] did not have resources to monitor all conversations, despite the introduction of the new censorship division.<ref>[http://www.ipn.gov.pl/portal.php?serwis=pl&dzial=345&id=4232&poz=3 Martial Law in Poland] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071014181417/http://www.ipn.gov.pl/portal.php?serwis=pl&dzial=345&id=4232&poz=3 |date=2007-10-14 }} {{pl icon}}</ref>
In [[Communist Romania|Romania]], [[telephone]] tapping was conducted by the General Directorate for Technical Operations of the [[Securitate]]. Created with [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] assistance in 1954, the outfit monitored all voice and electronic [[communication]]s in and out of Romania. They [[Covert listening device|bugged]] telephones and intercepted all [[telegraph]]s and [[teleprinter|telex]] messages, as well as placing [[microphone]]s in both public and private buildings.{{Citation needed|date=June 2013}}
==Fiction== The 2006 film ''[[The Lives of Others]]'' concerns a [[Stasi]] man who is telephone-tapping a suspected dissident writer.
The 1991 [[Poland|Polish]] comedy film ''[[Rozmowy kontrolowane]]'' (''Monitored Conversations'')<ref>{{IMDb title|0102815|Rozmowy kontrolowane}}</ref> capitalizes on this fact. The title alludes to the pre-recorded phrase "Rozmowa kontrolowana" ("The talk is being monitored") a person repeatedly hears during a phone conversation.
